We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms, including abdominal pain and vaginal spotting, indicate a possible ectopic pregnancy. The physical exam shows tenderness in the right adnexa, which is near the fallopian tubes where ectopic pregnancies often occur. The absence of rebound tenderness or tenderness at McBurney’s point rules out appendicitis. True diverticuli in the colon would indicate diverticulitis, but this is not consistent with the patient’s symptoms. A positive urinary beta-HCG and no intrauterine mass suggest an ectopic pregnancy, while a positive urinary beta-HCG and products of conception in the uterus would suggest a viable intrauterine pregnancy.
